{"cursor":"4276","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\nIn social science, a 'social relation' or 'social interaction' is any\nrelationship between two or more individuals. Social relations derived from\nindividual agency form the basis of social structure and the basic object for\nanalysis by social scientists. Fundamental inquiries into the nature of social\nrelations feature in the work of sociologists such as Max Weber in his theory of\nsocial action.\n\nCategorising social interactions enables observational and other social\nresearch, such as Gemeinschaft and Gesellschaft (lit. \"Community and Society\"),\ncollective consciousness, etc., however different schools and theories of\nsociology and other social sciences dispute the methods used for such\ninvestigations.\n","linknr":228,"url":"Social_interaction","recorded":1362509273,"links":38,"instances":["sociology","philosophy","sociology","social_theory"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Community building","Sociology index","Social concepts"],"headings":["Forms of relation and interaction","See also","Related disciplines","References","Bibliography","Further reading"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c7/SNA_segment.png/180px-SNA_segment.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki_88x31.png"],"tags":[["agency","sociology"],["action","philosophy"],["action","philosophy"],["group_action","sociology"],["reflexivity","social_theory"]],"members":["group_action","action","agency","reflexivity"],"related":["Social_science","Agency_(sociology)","Social_structure","Social_scientists","Max_Weber","Social_action","Gemeinschaft_and_Gesellschaft","Collective_consciousness","Sociology","Anthropology","Animal","Behavior","